        <!--  CHAPTER 1: FOR STUDENTS                                          -->
        <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="docs-chapter">
          <div class="docs-chapter__header">
            <span class="docs-chapter__num">01</span>
            <h2 class="docs-chapter__title">For Students</h2>
          </div>

          <section id="students-start" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Getting Started</h3>
            <p>You need exactly one thing: a <strong>GitHub account</strong>. No sign-up, no email, no password beyond GitHub itself. Your <code>@username</code> is your permanent identity across every course.</p>
            <p>Browse available courses at <a href={`${base}/courses`}>opencourses/courses</a>. Each course page shows difficulty, estimated hours, prerequisites, and the track it belongs to. Enrolling is one GitHub issue away.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="students-enroll" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Enrolling in a Course</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Open the course detail page and click <strong>Enroll</strong> — this creates a pre-filled GitHub issue using the <code>enrollment-request</code> template.</li>
              <li>The issue is labeled <code>enrollment-request</code> automatically.</li>
              <li><code>enroll.yml</code> fires, runs <code>engine/scripts/enroll.ts</code>, and:
                <ul>
                  <li>Validates the course slug exists</li>
                  <li>Checks you haven't already enrolled</li>
                  <li>Relabels the issue: <code>enrolled</code> + <code>course:&#123;slug&#125;</code></li>
                  <li>Posts a welcome comment with the course outline and first chapter instructions</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Your enrollment issue stays open for the duration of the course. All progress (chapter passes, final grade, certificate) is recorded here as labels and comments.</li>
            </ol>
            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout--info">One enrollment issue per course. Opening a second one for the same course will be rejected by the bot.</div>
          </section>

          <section id="students-learn" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Learning</h3>
            <p>Each course is structured into chapters. A chapter contains:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Lessons</strong> — videos, readings, or exercises. Links and descriptions are in the course content.</li>
              <li><strong>Chapter Test</strong> — a required assessment at the end of every chapter. You must pass it (score ≥ <code>pass_score</code>) before the next chapter unlocks.</li>
              <li><strong>Project</strong> (optional) — a hands-on project graded by the sandbox or manual review.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>All course content (lessons, question banks) is defined in <code>course.md</code> inside the engine repository. You can read it directly on GitHub.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="students-test" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Submitting Tests</h3>
            <p>To take a chapter test, open a new issue with the label <code>quiz-submit</code>. The issue body must follow this format:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>### Course
git-mastery

### Chapter
ch-01

### Answers

**Q1:** B
**Q2:** A, C
**Q3:** true
**Q4:** The index tracks staged changes ready for the next commit.

**Q5 (code):**
```python
def two_sum(nums, target):
    seen = &#123;&#125;
    for i, n in enumerate(nums):
        if target - n in seen:
            return [seen[target - n], i]
        seen[n] = i
```</code></pre>
            <p><strong>Answer formats by question type:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>MCQ</strong> — single letter: <code>B</code></li>
              <li><strong>Multi-select</strong> — comma-separated letters: <code>A, C</code></li>
              <li><strong>True/False</strong> — <code>true</code> or <code>false</code></li>
              <li><strong>Short answer</strong> — free text; the grader matches against keywords</li>
              <li><strong>Code</strong> — fenced code block with language tag</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section id="students-grading" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Grading & Scoring</h3>
            <p>The grader runs within seconds. It posts a result comment on your quiz issue:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>MCQ / True-False</strong> — exact match. 1 point per question.</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-select</strong> — partial credit: points proportional to correct answers selected (no penalty for wrong selections).</li>
              <li><strong>Short answer</strong> — keyword matching. You earn <code>matched / total_keywords</code> of the question's points. At least <code>min_keywords</code> must match to receive any credit.</li>
              <li><strong>Code</strong> — runs in an isolated Docker sandbox against static or dynamic test cases. Score = <code>passed_tests / total_tests × points</code>. No AI, no partial match — pure input/output.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The grader posts: <code>**Score:** 42/50 (84.0%) ✅ PASSED</code> or <code>❌ FAILED</code>.</p>
            <p>If you fail, you can re-attempt (up to <code>max_attempts</code> per chapter test). Open a new quiz-submit issue for the same chapter.</p>
            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout--warn">Code questions never share test cases between attempts — dynamic generators use a new random seed each run. You cannot memorize expected outputs.</div>
          </section>

          <section id="students-cert" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Certification</h3>
            <p>Certificate eligibility is configured per course:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Pass all chapter tests (required always)</li>
              <li>Achieve <code>min_overall_score</code> across all tests (e.g. 70%)</li>
              <li>Complete the final project, if required</li>
              <li>Pass the final exam, if present</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When you qualify, a maintainer runs <code>issue-cert.yml</code>. The workflow:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Generates a GPG-signed SVG certificate</li>
              <li>Embeds Open Badges 3.0 metadata (issuer, recipient, criteria)</li>
              <li>Publishes it as a GitHub Release on the repository</li>
              <li>Adds the <code>certified</code> label to your enrollment issue and closes it</li>
            </ol>
          </section>

          <section id="students-leader" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Leaderboard</h3>
            <p>Rankings are rebuilt nightly (02:00 UTC) and after every quiz pass. Your position is determined by four criteria, in order:</p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Average score</strong> — mean percentage across all graded chapter tests (higher is better)</li>
              <li><strong>Courses completed</strong> — more completed courses ranks higher</li>
              <li><strong>Total points earned</strong> — sum of all question points across all courses</li>
              <li><strong>Fastest course completion</strong> — time from enrollment to last chapter pass (lower is better)</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Your rank appears at <a href={`${base}/leaderboard`}>opencourses/leaderboard</a> automatically. A 🎓 badge marks certified students.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="students-labels" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Issue Labels</h3>
            <div class="docs-table-wrap">
              <table class="docs-table">
                <thead><tr><th>Label</th><th>Set By</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td><code>enrollment-request</code></td><td>Issue template</td><td>Triggers enrollment workflow</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>enrolled</code></td><td>Bot</td><td>Enrollment confirmed</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>course:&#123;slug&#125;</code></td><td>Bot</td><td>Which course this issue tracks</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>chapter-&#123;id&#125;-passed</code></td><td>Bot</td><td>Chapter test passed</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>course-complete</code></td><td>Bot</td><td>All chapters passed</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>certified</code></td><td>Bot</td><td>Certificate issued</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>quiz-submit</code></td><td>Issue template</td><td>Triggers quiz grader</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>project-submit</code></td><td>Issue template</td><td>Triggers project grader</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </section>
        </div>

        <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!--  CHAPTER 2: FOR COURSE CREATORS                                   -->
        <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="docs-chapter">
          <div class="docs-chapter__header">
            <span class="docs-chapter__num">02</span>
            <h2 class="docs-chapter__title">For Course Creators</h2>
          </div>

          <section id="creators-layout" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Course Directory Layout</h3>
            <p>Every course lives under <code>engine/courses/{'{'}slug{'}'}/</code>. Copy the template to start:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>cp -r engine/courses/template engine/courses/your-slug</code></pre>
            <p>Directory structure:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>engine/courses/your-slug/
├── course.md                ← single source of truth (edit this)
├── course.json              ← auto-generated on merge
├── contributors.json        ← auto-generated on merge
└── assets/
    ├── images/
    │   ├── banner.png       (1200×630 — course card)
    │   └── ch-01-diagram.svg
    ├── starter/             (starter code per chapter)
    │   └── ch-01/
    │       ├── starter.py
    │       └── README.md
    ├── solutions/           (reference solutions — keep gitignored)
    │   └── ch-01/solution.py
    ├── tests/               (dynamic test generators)
    │   └── q5-sort-gen.py
    ├── slides/              (PDF decks)
    │   └── ch-01-slides.pdf
    └── data/                (datasets)
        └── sample.csv</code></pre>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-frontmatter" class="docs-section">
            <h3>course.md Frontmatter Reference</h3>
            <p><code>course.md</code> uses YAML frontmatter. Every field is validated by <code>validate-pr.yml</code> on PR open.</p>
            <div class="docs-table-wrap">
              <table class="docs-table">
                <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.slug</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>URL-safe, lowercase, hyphens only. Permanent — never change after publish.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.title</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>Display name shown on the site.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.version</code></td><td>semver</td><td>✓</td><td>Bump on breaking curriculum changes.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.description</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>One clear paragraph (&lt;200 words) — what students will know after completing this.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.track</code></td><td>enum</td><td>✓</td><td>One of 12 tracks: <code>foundations</code> <code>languages</code> <code>web</code> <code>backend</code> <code>systems</code> <code>networks</code> <code>data</code> <code>security</code> <code>architecture</code> <code>creative</code> <code>emerging</code> <code>applied</code></td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.difficulty</code></td><td>enum</td><td>✓</td><td><code>beginner</code> <code>intermediate</code> <code>advanced</code></td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.tags</code></td><td>string[]</td><td>✓</td><td>Topic tags for filtering. Use lowercase-hyphens.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.prerequisites</code></td><td>string[]</td><td>✓</td><td>Array of course slugs that must be completed first. Use <code>[]</code> for none.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.estimated_hours</code></td><td>number</td><td>✓</td><td>Total study time in hours.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.thumbnail</code></td><td>path</td><td></td><td>Path to 1200×630 PNG/JPG banner image.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.license</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>Content license. Default: <code>CC BY-SA 4.0</code></td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>meta.repo</code></td><td>URL</td><td>✓</td><td>GitHub repo URL for star/fork counts.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>contributors[].name</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>Display name.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>contributors[].github</code></td><td>string</td><td>✓</td><td>GitHub username — canonical identity.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>contributors[].role</code></td><td>enum</td><td>✓</td><td><code>author</code> <code>reviewer</code> <code>translator</code> <code>illustrator</code> <code>maintainer</code></td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>contributors[].email</code></td><td>string</td><td></td><td>Not shown publicly. Used for git-log deduplication.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>certificate.requires_all_chapter_tests</code></td><td>bool</td><td>✓</td><td>Must all chapter tests be passed?</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>certificate.min_overall_score</code></td><td>0–100</td><td>✓</td><td>Minimum average score to receive certificate.</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>certificate.requires_final_project</code></td><td>bool</td><td>✓</td><td>Is a final project required?</td></tr>
                  <tr><td><code>certificate.final_test</code></td><td>ChapterTest</td><td></td><td>Optional grand final exam unlocked only after all chapters pass.</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-questions" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Question Types</h3>
            <p>All question types are supported in <code>chapter_test.questions[]</code> and lesson-level <code>quiz.questions[]</code>:</p>
            <div class="docs-table-wrap">
              <table class="docs-table">
                <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Key fields</th><th>Grading</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>mcq</code></td>
                    <td><code>options: string[]</code>, <code>answer: "A"</code></td>
                    <td>Exact match. 1 point.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>multi</code></td>
                    <td><code>options: string[]</code>, <code>answer: ["A","C"]</code></td>
                    <td>Partial credit: <code>correct_selected / total_correct × points</code>.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>true_false</code></td>
                    <td><code>answer: true</code></td>
                    <td>Exact match. 1 point.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>short</code></td>
                    <td><code>keywords: string[]</code>, <code>min_keywords: 2</code></td>
                    <td>Keyword match. <code>matched / total × points</code>. Zero if &lt; min_keywords matched.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>code</code></td>
                    <td><code>language</code>, <code>test_cases[]</code> or <code>test_generator</code></td>
                    <td><code>passed / total × points</code>. Runs in Docker sandbox.</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p>Supported code languages: <code>python</code> <code>javascript</code> <code>bash</code> <code>java</code> <code>go</code> <code>rust</code> <code>c</code> <code>cpp</code></p>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-generators" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Dynamic Test Generators</h3>
            <p>Instead of static test cases (which students can memorize), use a dynamic generator. The generator is a script that receives a seed and count:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>python assets/tests/q5-sort-gen.py --seed 42 --count 10</code></pre>
            <p>It must output a JSON array to stdout:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>[
  &#123;"input": "[3,1,4]", "expected_output": "[1,3,4]", "description": "basic sort"&#125;,
  &#123;"input": "[5,5,5]", "expected_output": "[5,5,5]", "hidden": true&#125;,
  ...
]</code></pre>
            <p>The grader calls your generator with a random seed on each attempt — students see different inputs every time. Reference it in your question:</p>
            <pre class="docs-pre"><code>- type: code
  language: python
  points: 10
  test_generator: ./assets/tests/q5-sort-gen.py
  starter_code: |
    def sort_list(nums):
        pass</code></pre>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-assets" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Assets</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>images/</strong> — Diagrams, screenshots, banner. Reference as <code>./assets/images/banner.png</code> in <code>thumbnail</code>.</li>
              <li><strong>starter/</strong> — Code handed to students. Organize by chapter: <code>starter/ch-01/starter.py</code>.</li>
              <li><strong>solutions/</strong> — Reference solutions. <strong>Add to <code>.gitignore</code> or keep on a private branch.</strong> The grader never reads this directory.</li>
              <li><strong>tests/</strong> — Dynamic test generator scripts. These are <em>committed</em> — they run on the CI server, not on the student's machine.</li>
              <li><strong>slides/</strong> — PDF slide decks. Link with the full raw GitHub URL.</li>
              <li><strong>data/</strong> — CSV, JSON, or other datasets for data-focused exercises.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-pr" class="docs-section">
            <h3>PR Workflow</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Create a branch: <code>git checkout -b course/your-slug</code></li>
              <li>Copy the template: <code>cp -r engine/courses/template engine/courses/your-slug</code></li>
              <li>Edit <code>course.md</code> — fill in all required fields</li>
              <li>Add assets to <code>assets/</code></li>
              <li>Open a PR targeting <code>main</code></li>
              <li><code>validate-pr.yml</code> runs automatically:
                <ul>
                  <li>Parses <code>course.md</code> and validates all fields</li>
                  <li>Checks for tampering of protected engine paths</li>
                  <li>Posts a validation report as a PR comment</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Fix any validation errors and push</li>
              <li>When the PR is merged:
                <ul>
                  <li><code>course-publish.yml</code> runs → generates <code>course.json</code> + <code>contributors.json</code></li>
                  <li><code>sync-site-data.yml</code> runs → aggregates all courses into <code>site/src/data/</code></li>
                  <li><code>deploy-site.yml</code> runs → rebuilds and deploys the site</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ol>
            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout--info">The slug in <code>meta.slug</code> is permanent once published. Changing it is a breaking change that breaks all existing enrollment issues for that course.</div>
          </section>

          <section id="creators-checklist" class="docs-section">
            <h3>Course Creator Checklist</h3>
            <ul class="docs-checklist">
              <li>Slug is lowercase-hyphen, globally unique</li>
              <li>Description is &lt;200 words and accurately describes outcomes</li>
              <li>Track slug is one of the 12 valid values</li>
              <li>All prerequisites exist as published courses</li>
              <li>Every chapter has a <code>chapter_test</code> with at least 3 questions</li>
              <li><code>pass_score</code> is set (50–90% recommended)</li>
              <li>Code questions have at least 5 test cases or a generator</li>
              <li>Short-answer questions have &ge;3 keywords</li>
              <li>Reference solutions are gitignored or on a private branch</li>
              <li>Banner image is 1200×630 px</li>
              <li>Your GitHub username is in <code>contributors[].github</code></li>
              <li><code>estimated_hours</code> is realistic (cross-check against lesson durations)</li>
            </ul>
          </section>
        </div>

